Troubleshooting Tips
Issue: Pre-commit command not found
# Add pip installation path to PATH
echo 'export PATH="$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH"' >> ~/.bashrc
source ~/.bashrc
Issue: Hooks not running on commit
# Reinstall hooks
pre-commit uninstall
pre-commit install
Issue: Black and Flake8 conflicts
Ensure .flake8 has extend-ignore = E203, W503 to avoid conflicts with Black formatting.

Issue: Bandit too strict
Adjust severity in .pre-commit-config.yaml:

args: ['-ll']  # Only report high severity issues
Issue: Slow hook execution
# Run specific hooks only
pre-commit run black --all-files
pre-commit run flake8 --all-files
Conclusion
You have successfully configured a pre-commit quality gate system that enforces code quality standards before code enters your repository. This setup includes:

Automated formatting with Black ensuring consistent code style
Linting with Flake8 catching common errors and style violations
Security scanning with Bandit identifying potential vulnerabilities
File validation preventing large files and ensuring proper formatting
This quality gate approach is essential in DevOps practices, preventing technical debt and security issues early in the development cycle. Pre-commit hooks serve as the first line of defense in maintaining code quality, reducing review time, and ensuring consistent standards across teams.

In production environments, these local checks are typically complemented by CI/CD pipeline checks, creating multiple layers of quality assurance. The skills learned here form the foundation for implementing comprehensive quality gates in enterprise DevOps workflows.
